# E2E Test Logging Guidelines

## Context

- When implementing logging in Playwright E2E tests for CI/CD environments
- When ensuring traceability and debugging capability in automated test runs
- When following SiMi directive requirements for production test logs

## Requirements

- Use standard `console.log` mechanism for CI/CD pipeline logging
- Structure logs with clear prefixes for automated filtering and analysis
- Log critical test steps and assertion checks for failure diagnosis
- Never log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, keys) in CI/CD logs
- Keep logs concise but informative for automated environments
- Ensure logs are machine-readable and searchable in CI/CD systems

## Log Prefixes

Use structured prefixes for different log types:

- `[SETUP_CHECK]` - Test precondition checking
- `[NAVIGATE]` - Page navigation actions
- `[TEST_STEP]` - Specific test steps
- `[ASSERTION_CHECK]` - Assertion verification
- `[DATA]` - Test data creation/modification
- `[API_REQUEST]` - API request information
- `[API_RESPONSE]` - API response status/data
- `[ERROR]` - Error occurrences

## Log Format for CI/CD

```text
[PREFIX] Descriptive message. { "key": "value" }
```

**CI/CD Considerations:**
- Logs should be parseable by automated systems
- Include timestamps for correlation with CI/CD pipeline events
- Use consistent formatting for log aggregation tools
- Avoid excessive nested JSON that bloats CI/CD logs

## Examples

<example>
**Good logging practice:**
```typescript
console.log('[TEST_STEP] Checking table visibility.');
await expect(userListPage.userTable).toBeVisible();

console.log('[ASSERTION_CHECK] Checking pagination text. Expected: "50", Actual: "25"');
await expect(page.getByText('50')).toBeVisible();
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
**Never log sensitive data:**
```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - exposes sensitive information
console.log(`[LOGIN] User password: ${password}`);
console.log(`[API] Token: ${authToken}`);
```
</example>

## Critical Rules for CI/CD

- Use structured prefixes for all log entries to enable automated log parsing
- Never log passwords, tokens, or sensitive data in CI/CD environments
- Log critical test steps and assertion checks for automated failure analysis
- Keep logs machine-readable and searchable in CI/CD systems
- Use English for consistency across automated environments
- Log API response status but not full response bodies to avoid log bloat
- Focus on logs that help diagnose failures in automated test runs
- Include expected vs actual values in assertion logs for CI/CD debugging
- Minimize verbose logging to reduce CI/CD log storage and processing costs
